'''Taka Shrine''' (たかじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} located in {{ill|lt=Haramachi Ward|Q24892679|WD=Q24892679|1=Haramachi-ku}}, {{ill|lt=Minamisōma City|Q642094|WD=Q642094|1=Minamisōma}}, {{ill|lt=Fukushima Prefecture|Q71707|WD=Q71707|1=Fukushima Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}} ({{ill|lt=Myōjin Taisha|Q9610964|WD=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}}) {{ill|lt=Ronsha|Q135022904|WD=Q135022904|1=Shikinai Ronsha}}, and under the {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=former shrine rank|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} it was designated as a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Prefectural Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}}.

=== Enshrined Deity ===
* '''{{ill|lt=Izanagi|Q813858|WD=Q813858|lt=Izanagi-no-Mikoto|1=Izanagi}}'''
*: According to *Ōsōshi*, a local historical record of the Sōma Domain, the shrine enshrines “Taka Ara-Mitama-no-Mikoto,” the {{ill|lt=Ara-mitama and Nigi-mitama|Q495568|WD=Q495568|lt=Ara-mitama|1=Mitama}} (rough spirit) of Izanagi-no-Mikoto.

The shintai (sacred object) has been prohibited from being viewed since ancient times and is therefore unknown. There is a theory that it may be a “hawk statue,” but this hawk statue is said to be the result of a mistaken transmission identifying the “White-Token Hawk” mentioned in shrine tradition as the shintai.

=== History ===
=== Overview ===
Taka Shrine is the foremost of the eight {{ill|lt=Shikinaisha|UNKNOWN|lt=Engishiki-listed shrines}} in {{ill|lt=Namekata District, Fukushima|Q11626139|WD=Q11626139|1=Namekata district}}, {{ill|lt=Mutsu Province|Q907389|WD=Q907389|1=Mutsu Province}} (Taka Shrine, {{ill|lt=Kashima Miko Shrine|Q11677124|WD=Q11677124|1=Kashima Miko Shrine}}, {{ill|lt=Mitachi Shrine|Q11488802|WD=Q11488802|1=Mito Shrine}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Masutamine Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Himatsuri Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}}, {{ill|lt=Takakura Shrine|Q11669904|WD=Q11669904|1=Takakura Shrine}}, {{ill|lt=Kanmuri Mine Shrine|Q11395049|WD=Q11395049|1=Sakamine Shrine}}, {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Oshio Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}}). Among shrines bearing the name “Taga Shrine,” it is the only one nationwide to have been granted the rank of {{ill|lt=Myōjin Taisha|Q9610964|WD=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}}, and it is said that Taga Shrines throughout the Tōhoku region originate from this shrine.

Although its exact origins are unknown, tradition holds that the shrine was founded in the 40th year of {{ill|lt=Emperor Keikō|Q329723|WD=Q329723|1=Emperor Keikō}} by {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Yamato Takeru|1=Yamato Takeru|WD=Q461258}}, who visited this area during his eastern campaign and enshrined the deity to pray for victory in battle. To the northwest of the current location lies the Furuuchi area, through which the Ōta River flows, and there is said to be a place called “Daimyōjin Kawara.” The ancient shrine site is said to have been on the southern hills of Daimyōjin Kawara. In the 7th year, 2nd month of {{ill|lt=Emperor Chūai|Q179971|WD=Q179971|1=Emperor Chūai}}, a violent storm washed away and severely damaged the shrine buildings, which drifted to the banks of the nearby Ōta River. In the 9th month of the same year, the shrine was relocated to Ashinodaira (present-day Jō-no-uchi, the current site).

In Kōryaku 2 ({{ill|lt=1380|Q6327|WD=Q6327|1=1380}}), there existed a bronze bell (waniguchi) bearing an inscription of donation by Fujiwara Yoshimori, which is said to hang in the inner sanctuary of the main hall. From April of Jōō 4, Kinoe-mi year ({{ill|lt=1655|Q6975|WD=Q6975|1=1655}}) to Meireki 1 (the same year), the shrine sanctuary was repaired, with timber donated by {{ill|lt=Sōma Tadatane|Q8514579|WD=Q8514579|1=Sōma Tadatane}}. During the {{ill|lt=Genroku|Q1325001|WD=Q1325001|1=Genroku}} era, {{ill|lt=Sōma Masatane|Q8514599|WD=Q8514599|1=Sōma Masatane}} built a sanctuary called “Yōshinden,” associated with {{ill|lt=Yoshida Shintō|Q1760351|WD=Q1760351|1=Yoshida Shintō}}, within the castle grounds, and at that time, for certain reasons, had a statue of the “White-Token Hawk” carved and dedicated to Taka Shrine. This wooden statue of the “White-Token Hawk” is said to have been stored in a miniature shrine. Even today, the “White-Token Hawk Statue” is enshrined in the main hall as a sacred treasure. According to shrine tradition, although it appears to be an ordinary wooden statue, it was named “White-Token Hawk” because the feathers appear white depending on how the light strikes them.

In Kyōhō 9 ({{ill|lt=1724|Q6926|WD=Q6926|1=1724}}), Sōma Masatane donated shrine lands amounting to 1 koku and 9 to, among other offerings, and the shrine received deep reverence from successive lords of the Sōma Domain.

In Meiji 6 ({{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|WD=Q7757|1=1873}}), it was designated a village shrine, and in Shōwa 19 ({{ill|lt=1944|Q5268|WD=Q5268|1=1944}}), it was elevated to a prefectural shrine.

Taka Shrine has long been believed to bestow divine benefits such as longevity, fulfillment of wishes, household safety, safe childbirth, maritime safety, and abundant catches. Because it was originally enshrined to pray for victory in battle, many worshippers in particular visit to pray for certain victory in elections.

=== Court Rank ===
* Enryaku 15 ({{ill|lt=796|Q33452|WD=Q33452|1=796}}) 10th month, 22nd day: Junior Fifth Rank, Lower Grade (*{{ill|lt=Nihon Kōki|Q1077029|WD=Q1077029|1=Nihon Kōki}}*) – recorded as “Taga Shrine.”

