=== History ===
The founding date of Kifune Shrine is unknown, but it is said to have been worshipped since before Genkō 3 (1323). According to *Ōsōshi*, there is a record stating that the box housing the sacred object bears an inscription indicating it was made in the 5th year of Hōen, kinoe-mi year, 8th month. The sacred object is said to be a statue “riding a dragon and wearing white robes.” In Bunji 5, when {{ill|lt=Sōma Moritsune|Q11582495|WD=Q11582495|1=Sōma Moritsune}} took control of Namekata District, he designated Kifune Shrine as the district’s chief shrine and deeply revered it, carrying out embellishments of the shrine buildings. Kifune Shrine was mainly worshipped as a deity of rainmaking and stopping rain, bountiful harvests, success and advancement in life, and martial arts.

According to *Ōsōshi*, Taka Shrine once existed within the precincts of Kibune (Kifune) Shrine in Minami-Odaka Village. It was a shrine building measuring 2 shaku 5 sun in depth. It was a shrine enshrined during the era of Emperor Keikō, with Izanagi-no-Mikoto and Takamimusubi-no-Mikoto as the two main deities, and Koyō Myōjin as an accompanying deity.

In Bunka 12 (1815), the lord of the Sōma Domain, {{ill|lt=Sōma Masutane|Q8514605|WD=Q8514605|1=Sōma Masutane}}, ordered shrine priests and a man named Watanabe Yoshitsuna to investigate and identify the eight Shikinaisha in Namekata District. Watanabe Yoshitsuna reported that the Engishiki-listed Myōjin Taisha known as Taka Shrine was the Taka Daimyōjin enshrined within the grounds of Kōmyō-ji Temple in Taka Village. In response, Takadama Tanba, a shrine priest of the Kibune Shrine in Odaka Village, submitted a counter-report claiming that Taka Shrine was a small shrine enshrined in Odaka Village.

According to that report, Taka Shrine was a shrine where the Yasakani no Magatama, one of the Three Sacred Treasures, was enshrined as the local tutelary deity, and it had long been the guardian deity of Odaka Village. The ancestors of the shrine priest family originally bore the name “Takadama,” but out of deference to Taka Shrine they changed it to “Takadama.” The Taga faith’s head shrine, {{ill|lt=Taga Taisha|Q402091|WD=Q402091|1=Taga-taisha}} in Shiga Prefecture, is called “O-Taga-sama,” and the name Odaka is said to derive from calling the enshrined Taka Shrine “Mi-Taka.” The Takadama family administered the rites of both Kifune Shrine and Taka Shrine, which were enshrined near {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Sōma Odaka Shrine|1=UNKNOWN}} in Odaka Ward. Taka Shrine was located at a place called Nihonmatsu in Odaka Village, about ten ken from Kifune Shrine. Later, Taka Shrine was washed away by a flood during the Genroku era, but a farmer recovered the small shrine from the water and it was enshrined together within the precincts of Kifune Shrine.

Takadama Tanba wrote down the above origins of Taka Shrine in Odaka Village and reported them to the domain. However, according to the compiler of *Ōsōshi*:
* In shrine identification surveys conducted before the domain’s Bunka 12 investigation, Taka Shrine of Odaka Village is not recorded.
* Records of the Shima family, shrine priests of Taka Shrine in Taka Village, appear in shrine priest registries from Genroku 15 and in temple and shrine surveys from the Shōtoku era, whereas records of the Takadama family only appear from Kanpō 1 onward.

For these reasons, the theory of Takadama Tanba is said to contain many doubtful points.

At present, the inscription on the stone monument describing the shrine’s origins at the entrance of Kifune Shrine’s approach states that the enshrined deities are Takaokami-no-Kami and Yamiokami-no-Kami, and that Taka Shrine is enshrined together in the same sanctuary.

